Introduction

This report seeks to build a logistic regression model that would be used to predict diagnosis of diabetes based on a number of factors. The analysis uses diabetes dataset that has several variables. However, for this report, the following variables are utilized; age, gender, weight, height, insurance, smoking, cholesterol and whether one has diabetes or not.

Data Cleaning/Preparation

This section provides the data cleaning/preparation.

setwd("/Users/lealenabefikadu/Downloads")   
#opened file and set it equal to a variable
diabetes <- read.csv("diabetes.csv", header = TRUE)
diabetes$height.si=diabetes$height*0.0254
diabetes$weight.si=diabetes$height*0.453592

diabetes$BMI = diabetes$weight.si/diabetes$height.si^2

attach(diabetes)
diabetes$bmi_categorised[BMI < 18.5] <- "underweight"
diabetes$bmi_categorised[BMI >= 18.5  & BMI < 25] <- "normal"
diabetes$bmi_categorised[BMI > 25  & BMI <= 30] <- "overweight"
diabetes$bmi_categorised[BMI > 30] <- "obese"

diabetes$insurance = factor(diabetes$insurance, 
                     levels = c(0, 1, 2), 
                     labels = c("none", "government", "private"))
diabetes$smoking = factor(diabetes$smoking, 
                            levels = c(1, 2, 3), 
                            labels = c("current", "never", "ex-smoker"))

A total 403 participants took part in this study (n = 403 observations). In terms of BMI categorization, 98.8% (n = 398) of the participants were categorized as under weight, the remaining 1.2% (n = 5) were missing. Majority of the participants (58.1%, n = 234) were female participants with 41.9% (n = 169) representing male participants in the study. Only 15.4% (n = 60) of the participants were diagnosed with diabetes. The remaining 84.6% (n = 330) were non-diabetic. The average age of the participants was 46.85 years old (SD = 16.31) while the average body mass index (BMI) was 10.69 (SD = 0.64).

The first graph (Figure 1) presents a bar chart of insurance. As can be seen, majority (n = 147) had government insurance and were closely followed with private insurance holders (n = 139). However, it is crucial to note that a significant number (n = 117) did not have any insurance.

The second graph (Figure 2 above) presents a bar chart of smoking status. As can be seen, majority (n = 223) had never smoked in their life and were distantly followed by current smokers (n = 121). Close to half of the current smokers (n = 59) self-reported as ex-smokers and they were the minority in the study.

The third graph (Figure 3 above) presents a scatter plot of cholesterol levels versus BMI. As can be seen, there seems to be no relationship between these two variables (cholesterol levels and BMI).

The four graph (Figure 4 above) presents a histogram of Age. As can be seen, the histogram shows that age is positively skewed/right skewed with longer tail to the right.

Logistic regression

In this section, we build a logistic regression model with diabetes (dm) as the outcome variable, and age, gender, and BMI as the predictors. The results of the analysis are presented below.

glm.fit <- glm(dm ~ age+gender+BMI, data = diabetes, family = binomial)
summary(glm.fit)

From the above results, it can be seen that only one of the predictor variables is significant in the model. The significant predictor variable is age (p < 0.05). The other two variables (dummy variable for male and BMI) are insignificant in the model (p > 0.05).

The coefficient of age is given as 0.0575; this suggests that a positive relationship exists between diabetes and age. As one ages, we would expect the likelihood of such an individual to be diagnosed with diabetes to increase. In fact, a unit increase in age is expected to result in a 6% increase in the odds of one being diagnosed with diabetes. Similarly, a unit decrease in age is expected to result in a 6% decrease in the odds of one being diagnosed with diabetes.

The coefficient of dummy variable male is given as -0.5306; this suggests that a negative relationship exists between dummy variable male and age. Male participants have less chances of being diagnosed with diabetes as compared . In fact, being a male results in a 41% decrease in the odds of being diagnosed with diabetes.

The coefficient of BMI is given as -0.6062; this suggests that a negative relationship exists between diabetes and BMI. As BMI increases, we would expect the likelihood of an individual being diagnosed with diabetes to decrease. In fact, a unit increase in BMI is expected to result in a 45% decrease in the odds of one being diagnosed with diabetes. Similarly, a unit decrease in BMI is expected to result in a 45% decrease in the odds of one being diagnosed with diabetes.
